      <h2 id="oci-plus-input-data">OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview Input Data</h2>
      <p>The models that underpin the Oil Climate Index (OCI)<a id="footnote-ref-1" href="#methodology/footnote-1" class="same-page-nav footnote-inline"><sup>1</sup></a> require consistent, comparable, and verifiable open access data on oil and gas resources. This includes oil assays (analyses of predetermined data measuring a crude oil’s chemical and physical characteristics) that are reported out in a specified format, upstream field-level equipment and operating specifications, midstream refining process input requirements, and downstream transport and end-use data.</p>
      <p>In the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview, we present a sample of 29 diverse oil and gas resources. We went through an intensive process to obtain data on 75 sample oils and 35 sample gases, all of which will be included in the forthcoming full version of the OCI<sup>+</sup>. We used hundreds of academic sources, technical documents, and reports from industry news to identify data. In doing so, we compiled a list of alternate names for our resources, since many oil and gas fields are recorded using slightly different names by our wide range of sources. The list of OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview aliases can be found in <a href="assets/resources/appendex-a.docx">Appendix A</a>. Oil and gas resources were selected based on their geographic, geologic, chemical, and physical diversity. But the final arbiter of the global resources selected was data availability. There were resources that we would have selected save for the lack of transparent data. </p>
      <p><strong>OPGEE</strong> (the Oil Production Greenhouse Gas Emissions Estimator) technically requires up to 50 data inputs, but the use of smart defaults allows the model to assign reasonable estimates based on just a few key characteristics. For upstream data inputs for the OCI's sample resources, including references and sources, see the workbook.</p>
      <p><strong>PRELIM</strong> (the Petroleum Refinery Life-Cycle Inventory Model) requires crude oil assays that use a specified number of temperature cuts. Assays provided in a different format (for example, too few temperature cuts or different temperature bands) must be adjusted using an openly available transformation tool—a process that can introduce errors into PRELIM. In the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview web tool, the assay sources for the sample oils are specified in the “oil details” pages. The assay data used in OCI calculations are available in the PRELIM model workbook on the “Assay Inventory” worksheet.</p>
      <p><strong>OPGEM</strong> (the Oil and Gas Products Emissions Module) data inputs require a detailed product slate (measured in barrels per day for liquid products, kilograms per day for solid products, or gas density for gaseous products), which are reported out in PRELIM. Petroleum coke, LPG, and petrochemical feedstock densities are used to convert solid and gaseous petroleum products to barrels. For density purposes, it is assumed that petrochemical feedstock is one-half ethane and one-half propane, while LPG is one-half propane and one-half butane. Barrels per day of product are then converted into barrels of product per BOE processed oil and gas by multiplying by the ratio of oil into the refinery by adjust refined volume at equilibrium and dividing by the total oil and gas volume processed in OPGEE. For GHGs from end use, the barrels of each product per BOE are multiplied by emission factors in the case of petroleum fuels and for petrochemical feedstock we use EPA reported estimated emissions to convert petrochemical feedstock to ethylene. For the GHGs from product transport, we divide products in to liquid light, liquid heavy, solid, and gas, and make assumptions that the user can change for the distance traveled and shipping mode. Shipping vehicle and fuel emissions factors are obtained from the Argonne National Laboratory’s GREET (Greenhouse Gases, Regulated Emissions, and Energy Use in Transportation) Model. End-use emissions from the combustion of petroleum products are calculated using U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) emissions factors. </p>
      <ol>
        <li><em>Distance:</em> Given current limitations posed by the reporting of global petroleum product transport data, the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview assumes that lighter petroleum liquid products (petrochemical feedstocks, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, NGL, LPG) are transported via pipeline 2,414 kilometers or 1,500 miles (the equivalent distance from Houston to New York) and then by heavy-duty tanker truck 380 kilometers or 236 miles (the equivalent distance to either the Washington, DC or Boston metropolitan areas). Heavy liquid products (fuel Oil, residual fuels) are assumed to travel 1,200 km by rail, 1,200 km by tanker, and 500 miles by truck. Solid fuels (petroleum coke and sulfur, which is not currently included but should be in an OGPEM 2.0) are assumed to travel 3,352 km by tanker and 750 miles by rail. Gas is assumed to move via pipeline an estimated 2,414 km unless it is transported as LNG in a tanker in the case of Australia Gorgon or Qatar Idd El Shargi.</li>
        <li><em>Price:</em> Adding natural gas (compressed and LNG) along with NGLs and petrochemical feedstock makes it more difficult to ascertain product spot prices, which are not consistently available in an open-source format for many petroleum products. OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview eliminates the metric basis (per $ product and per $ crude oil) from the analysis. This may be added back for user assumptions in a future version.</li>
      </ol>
