      <h2 id="oci-plus-modeling-methods">OCI<sup>+</sup> Modeling Methods</h2>
        <p>OPGEE and PRELIM are distinct models that are run separately. However, any oil present in wet gas processing is then input into PRELIM that usually necessitates the use of a proxy assay. The gas outputs from OPGEE and the oil outputs from PRELIM are product inputs into OGPEM. The resulting GHG outputs of the three models are then summed to calculate total GHG emissions. All outputs are converted into the same functional units before they are summed. The default unit is kilograms CO<sub>2</sub> equivalent emissions per barrel of oil equivalent (of processed oil and gas). End product and co-product combustion is generally reported out in OGPEM, regardless of where in the supply chain it is generated (for example, net upstream petcoke from upgrading and midstream petcoke from deep conversion refining or processed gas that is handled upstream). However, if data exist, use of co-products in upstream processes is also taken into account; this is evident in the use of upstream petcoke in extra-heavy oil upgrading.</p>
        <p>Discrepancies and inconsistencies in OCI model inputs can occur because of different public data sources and lack of coordinated data collection. For example, discrepancies can arise in API gravity inputs into OPGEE and PRELIM. We use the assay gravity for both OPGEE and PRELIM inputs. The only exception is in the case of upgraded oil sands where the plotted gravity is that of raw bitumen (the input oil) rather than the synthetic crude oil that results after processing. The API gravity presented in the web tool is derived from the oil assays used in PRELIM, because this model’s emissions estimates are more sensitive to API gravity than OPGEE’s, where changes in API gravity generally do not make a material difference in upstream GHG results.</p>
        <p>When there is no directly corresponding assay for an OPGEE oil field or associated oil from a gas field, a proxy assay is selected that closely fits the sample oil’s characteristics. As actual assays are collected, proxy assays will be replaced. The current use of proxy assays in OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview are noted on the Oil Details pages for each oil and gas and discussed in Special Cases below.</p>
      <h3>OPGEE Version 3.0</h3>
        <p>Link to the model workbook hosted by Stanford University: <a href="https://pangea.stanford.edu/researchgroups/eao/research/opgee-oil-production-greenhouse-gas-emissions-estimator" target="_blank">https://pangea.stanford.edu/researchgroups/eao/research/opgee-oil-production-greenhouse-gas-emissions-estimator</a>.</p>
        <p>The field and resource data specified are used to generate OPGEE’s bulk assessment tool for each resource, which is then used to calculate base-run GHG emissions outputs for each oil and gas run.
        <p>OPGEE considers the transport of oil to the refinery inlet and gas to the distribution hub. In the preview tool, the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview continues to assume that all oil is transported from its country of origin to Houston via the mode that is nearest to the oil field. On the gas side, the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview assumes that compressed natural gas (CNG) is transported by pipeline from the field to a major city or hub within its region (i.e. North American gas is sent to Henry Hub). Liquefied natural gas (LNG) are special cases in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview. In the OCI<sup>+</sup>, we will build out LNG transport and regasification and CNG shipment specifications. We do not expect this to have a material change in OGPEM’s estimated GHG emissions. A user designated option is planned to allow for special cases to be modeled for natural gas transport and end use options, which can vary widely.</p>
        <p>In the case of petcoke produced upstream during oil-sand and extra-heavy-oil upgrading, a separate calculation in OPGEE is used to estimate the net petcoke produced. This considers the OPGEE-derived portion of petcoke used as an upstream energy source and subtracts that from the total petcoke production reported by the <a href="https://www.aer.ca/documents/sts/ST39.pdf" target="_blank">Alberta Energy Regulator</a>. Lacking detailed reporting in Venezuela, OPGEE uses the average relative amounts of petcoke production reported for Canadian oil sands for Venezuelan extra-heavy-oil upgrading.</p>
        <p>The OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview web tool has several upstream oil and gas field operating parameters that users can modify. These adjustments reflect variations to OPGEE inputs that have been pre-loaded as static model runs. In the future completed OCI<sup>+</sup> web tool, user adjustments will change OPGEE 3.0 inputs and generate live, new model runs.  Reductions and increases are calculated off a 100 percent base, unless otherwise specified, for the flaring emissions intensity, venting emissions intensity, fugitive emissions intensity, and the emissions intensity of steam (simulating solar-powered steam generation). Users can adjust these operating assumptions on the Supply Chain and Analysis web tool pages. On these pages, users can also adjust the percent of natural gas and associated gas liquefied as LNG. Most resources default to zero percent LNG (two exceptions: Australia Gorgon defaults to 100 percent; Qatar Idd El Shargi defaults to 50 percent). Runs that model increases of 50 and 100 percent of gas liquefied and shipped as LNG are available for the following resources: Nigeria Obagi, Australia Cossack, Azerbaijan Azeri, US Texas Spraberry, US Eagle Ford all zones, UAE Shah, New Zealand Kapuni, China Sulige, and Iran South Pars. </p>
        <p>Under California regulations, OPGEE reports GHG-emissions outputs in units of kilogram CO<sub>2</sub> equivalent per megajoule of petroleum products generated. These outputs are converted into emissions per barrel of oil equivalent by multiplying them by the weighted lower heating value of all processed oil and gas products (in megajoule per barrel of oil equivalent).</p>
      <h4>OPGEE Flaring Emissions Estimation and Mapping Boundaries in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview Web Tool</h4>
        <p>Flaring emissions were estimated by aligning satellite measurements of flares with outlines of the oil fields. The flares and volumes were identified with data from the Visible Infrared Imaging Radiometer Suite (VIIRS) sensor, which, when combined with the Nightfire Algorithm, can detect and provide estimates to quantify flare location and volume<a id="footnote-ref-2" href="#methodology/footnote-2" class="same-page-nav footnote-inline"><sup>2</sup></a>. The Nightfire Algorithm, developed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), develops annual estimates for flaring volumes and aggregates the data into a spatial database that designates the type of flare as production, refining, or processing. The flaring rates reflect 2017 upstream flaring volumes located within the oil fields.</p>
        <p>In order to determine which flares should be included, the geographic extent of each field was determined. The location and areal extent for each field was collected from publicly available data where available. Location data were also aggregated from the Petroleum Economist’s <em>World Energy Atlas</em><a id="footnote-ref-3" href="#methodology/footnote-3" class="same-page-nav footnote-inline"><sup>3</sup></a>. The Atlas provides maps of oil fields across the world, as well as a number of oil-associated infrastructure projects (for example, pipelines and loading terminals). Each available image (regardless of source) was overlaid with satellite imagery from Google Earth before oil field boundaries were generated. These boundaries were drawn liberally to ensure that all visible surface infrastructure is included within the flaring estimation boundary. In many cases, the final boundary including surface infrastructure is larger than the field boundaries reported in public maps or the <em>World Energy Atlas</em>. For offshore fields, boundaries are placed to focus on production and processing platforms, where visible from Google Earth imagery.</p>
        <p>Within each field boundary, flared volumes were summed to determine total flaring emissions from the field. Not all oil fields contained satellite flare data. Many offshore fields use floating production storage and offloading (FPSOs) vessels that navigate the waters around the field. FPSOs are responsible for flaring associated with offshore fields. For offshore fields that did not contain flares (in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview these were Australia Cossack, Australia Gorgon, and Mexico Chuc) flares in a close radius of the fields were selected.</p>
        <p>For four onshore fields (U.S. California Midway Sunset, U.S. California South Belridge, UAE Shah, and New Zealand Kapuni), flares proximal to the field boundaries were selected. The <em>World Energy Atlas</em> was used to confirm that these flares could not be attributed to any other nearby fields. It was confirmed that these flaring values were comparable to the 2014 flare data used in OCI Phase 2. This method provides more accurate flaring rate estimates than assuming a default flaring rate for these fields.</p>
        <h4>OPGEE Venting Emissions Estimation</h4>
          <p>The OCI up through Phase 2 was concerned with the production of oil resources and their associated emissions, primarily carbon dioxide. However, a global increase in natural gas production ushered in a heightened importance of properly estimating venting and fugitive methane emissions. During the preparation of OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview, the OPGEE model was not as optimized to estimate venting methane emissions as it was for fugitive methane. The International Energy Agency (IEA) provides the best currently available estimates. See Tables 9 and 10 <a href="https://www.iea.org/media/weowebsite/2017/WEM_Documentation_WEO2017.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>. IEA splits out vented methane emissions for both onshore and offshore production sites. All emission values are based on the United States and can be scaled to estimate global emissions using a country multiplier. OPGEE results are the default for methane venting; however, when the venting webtool slider is in use, OPGEE venting values are subtracted out and replaced with IEA values.</p>
      <h3>PRELIM Version 1.3</h3>
        <p>Link to the model workbook hosted by the University of Calgary: <a href="http://www.ucalgary.ca/lcaost/PRELIM">http://www.ucalgary.ca/lcaost/PRELIM</a>. </p>
        <p>PRELIM version 1.3 contains 149 oil assays in its inventory. These assays are run through the “Results All Assays” macro three times (see the workbook for this macro). Each PRELIM run corresponds to a different refinery
            configuration—hydroskimming, medium conversion, and deep conversion (the last two with fluid catalytic cracking and gas-oil hydrocracking units). These three runs are then repeated with PRELIM’s methane-only switch turned on, in order to isolate
            methane emissions for each oil through each refinery configuration.</p>
        <p>The default refinery is chosen by PRELIM using an API gravity and sulfur-content categorization scheme, as summarized below. Users can run oils through different refinery configurations in the OCI web tool to estimate how GHG emissions change.
            However, this option is not included in the OCI<sup>+ </sup>Preview web tool. Go to PRELIM to employ this detailed analysis of non-default refinery runs.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Deep conversion refinery—heavy crude (15 to 22 API) with any sulfur level</li>
            <li>Medium conversion refinery—medium sweet crude (22 to 32 API, with less than 0.5 percent sulfur content by weight); medium sour crude (22 to 32 API, with more than 0.5 percent sulfur content by weight); and light sour crude (over 32 API, with
                more than 0.5 percent sulfur content by weight)</li>
            <li>Hydroskimming refinery—light sweet crude (over 32 API, with less than 0.5 percent sulfur content by weight)</li>
        </ul>
        <p><em>The exceptions among our sample oils are discussed in the “Special Cases” section below.</em></p>
        <p>PRELIM version 1.3 by default uses a float case, allowing product volumes to be determined by the optimal use of refinery process units for processing individual, unblended oils. This version of PRELIM also allows users to specify output ratios
            for products like gas, diesel, and jet fuel, among others, in the “Expert Input” sheet. In order to use this tool, the following add-ins must be selected for use: Analysis ToolPak, Analysis ToolPak - VBA, and Solver Add-In.</p>
        <p>Co-products, including petrochemical feedstock, asphalt, and petcoke, can be turned on and off by users. A crude blending tool was added in PRELIM version 1.1 and was further expanded in Phase 3. Additionally, a hydrogen surplus that results from
            lighter oils is noted but not credited for these oils or debited to heavier oils in PRELIM version 1.1.</p>
        <p>The OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview runs PRELIM 1.3 was run with petrochemical feedstock “on” and also reports out liquid petroleum gas (LPG) outputs. Petrochemicals (assumed to be 50/50 ethane and propane) and LPG (assumed to be 50/50 propane and
            butane) are reported out in their gaseous state. In order to convert this to an equivalent in liquid barrels per day for use in OGPEM, we obtain a conversion factor by dividing the liquid density of the two products by their gas density. Dividing
            this conversion factor into PRELIM outputs in barrels per day delivers the result for these gaseous petrochemical products. Other model assumptions are provided in the <a
              href="https://www.ucalgary.ca/lcaost/files/lcaost/prelim-v1.3-documentation.pdf">PRELIM User Guide and Technical Documentation (PDF</a>).</p>
      <h3>OPGEM Version 1.0</h3>
        <p>The OPEM model workbook that was developed for OCI 2.0 can be found in the “OPEM 2.0 Runs” sheet of the main workbook. We are currently converting OPEM to OGPEM to include gas co-products from oil and gas production.</p>
        <p>An overriding goal of OGPEM is to include final liquid, gas, and solid petroleum product use in the default GHG emissions calculation—and thereby avoid carbon leakage from—all petroleum products and co-products. Historically, petroleum end use has
            centered on transport fuels, including gasoline and diesel, and has ignored or incompletely and inconsistently reported GHG emissions from petroleum co-products like petcoke, fuel oil, residual fuels, asphalt, and petrochemical feedstocks. OGPEM
            version 1.0 includes these co-products; those that are not yet displayed in the web tool (e.g., asphalt, sulfur) will be added to a revised OCI<sup>+</sup> webtool. </p>
        <p>The default product slate output from PRELIM can be found in the worksheet “PRELIM Product Slates” in the OGPEM workbook. Alternative product slates can be generated by running the PRELIM model.</p>
        <p>Petcoke production (both in production-heavy oil upgrading in OPGEE and refining in PRELIM) defaults to 100 percent combustion and can be adjusted down to 50 percent and zero in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview web tool. For the OCI<sup>+</sup>
            Preview, asphalt was run “off” and petrochemical feedstock was run “on.” Additionally, for the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview, we assume all NGL is used as petrochemical feedstock. </p>
        <p>OGPEM uses emissions factors reported by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency for GHG inventories, updated in November 2015. These emissions factors are documented <a
              href="https://www.epa.gov/sites/production/files/2015-12/documents/emission-factors_nov_2015.pdf">here</a>. Note that the EPA assumes near-complete fuel combustion in the calculation of published emissions factors. Depending on the quality of
            the engine in which a fuel is burned, EPA emissions factors may result in a best-case (lowest emissions) estimate. This will be investigated in the OCI<sup>+</sup>. Although emission factors have not changed in a material way, EPA emission
            factors for fuel combustion have been updated <a href="https://www.epa.gov/sites/production/files/2018-03/documents/emission-factors_mar_2018_0.pdf">here</a>. These will be incorporated into the next phase of the OCI<sup>+</sup>. However, EPA has
            not updated its GWP to AR5. The OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview uses AR5 GWPs; this is discussed above under Global Warming Potential.</p>
