      <h3>User-Defined Sliders</h3>
        <p>Emissions drivers are derived from operating decisions that can affect an oil’s and/or a gas’ GHG emissions. The web tool allows users to alter model parameters for steam production, gas liquefaction, flaring intensity, venting intensity, fugitives intensity, and renewable hydrogen, using sliders on the Supply Chain and View Details pages. Steam, gas liquefaction, flaring, venting, and fugitives sliders alter relevant OPGEE inputs, while steam and renewable hydrogen alter PRELIM inputs. The petcoke slider also alters OGPEM outputs. </p>
        <p>Note on the venting, flaring, and fugitives sliders: The venting, flaring, and fugitives sliders are not linked—for example, adjustments made to the venting slider do not affect the fugitive slider, and vice versa. This implies that a volume of gas handled at a field is not fixed. In this way, these sliders can be combined to represent a worst-case scenario, in which venting and fugitive emissions are additive.</p>
      <h3>Analysis Regression Lines</h3>
        <p>Regression lines presented on the Analysis page are calculated using the simple ordinary least squares (OLS) regression method.</p>
      <h3>Methane Map</h3>
        <p>Unlike the flaring data and map, the methane map does not reflect the methane estimations used in the estimation of GHG emissions for the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview oils and gases. Methane emissions are estimated in OPGEE, with the exception of venting emissions, which are supplemented by IEA values, as described above. The methane map was obtained from analysis by Harvard professor and NASA affiliate Dr. Daniel Jacob, whose research is linked <a href="http://acmg.seas.harvard.edu/">here</a>. Dr. Jacob and his team used global methane data collected 2010 to 2015 from the Japanese TANSO-GOSAT instrument in a global inverse <a href="https://www.atmos-chem-phys.net/19/7859/2019/">analysis</a>. The image highlights methane hotspots around the world and is overlaid with OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview fields and GHG footprints. Dr. Jacob and his team are now analyzing new TROPOMI data that will be included in a future version of the OCI<sup>+</sup> web tool.</p>
      <h2 id="special-cases">Special Cases</h2>
      <h3>OPGEE Special Cases</h3>
        <h4>Modeling Multiple Zones</h4>
        <p>U.S. Texas Eagle Ford is modeled as four different fields in OPGEE 3.0 to account for the fact that the Eagle Ford formation contains different horizontal production zones that use different production practices to extract
            different volumes of different types of resource (e.g., black, volatile, condensate, and gas). These processes impact upstream emissions differently. The locations of each zone affect the calculation of flaring associated with each, since flaring
            values are calculated spatially in conjunction with NASA’s VIIRS satellite instrument whose data is then analyzed by NOAA. </p>
        <h4>CO<sub>2</sub> EOR</h4>
        <p>U.S. Wyoming LaBarge is a gas field known for its extremely high CO<sub>2</sub> content (66%), which is used for CO<sub>2</sub>-EOR (Enhanced Oil Recovery) at the nearby Salt Creek oil field. Some CO<sub>2</sub>-EOR operations qualify for a GHG
            emissions credit because they capture carbon dioxide from industrial exhaust. Wyoming LaBarge does not qualify, however, because its carbon dioxide is pulled out of an underground source in which it had already been naturally stored. For this
            reason, a U.S. Wyoming field is used in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview web tool as a <em>Natural CO<sub>2</sub> EOR Example</em><strong><em>. </em></strong>Meanwhile, CO<sub>2</sub> capture for EOR purposes are being <a
              href="https://www.hartenergy.com/exclusives/adnoc-harnesses-co2-increase-oil-recovery-30742">adopted</a> by oil companies in the Middle East and North Africa. For this reason, a United Arab Emirates field is used as a <em>Manmade CO<sub>2</sub>
                EOR Example</em><strong> </strong>that uses CO<sub>2</sub> that is sequestered from manmade sources. A complete database compiled by the IEA for enhanced oil recovery projects is available <a
              href="https://www.iea.org/newsroom/news/2018/november/whatever-happened-to-enhanced-oil-recovery.html">here</a>. </p>
        <h4>Upgraded Synthetic Crude Oils</h4>
        <p>Canada Athabasca DC SCO is an unconventional oil sands resource, one of several that was modeled in the OCI that has been retained in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview. Oil sands and extra-heavy oil production practices differ widely. (An infographic
            describing these techniques can be found <a href="http://www.npr.org/2012/08/16/158907708/infographic-how-tar-sands-oil-is-produced">here</a>.) This oil is upgraded to a synthetic crude oil (SCO) before being shipped to a refinery. As such, its
            petcoke is produced upstream and added to the total estimated transport and combustion emissions in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview. Additional oil sands and extra-heavy oils are planned to be included and updated in the OCI<sup>+</sup> web tool in
            the future. Note that the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview classifies this oil as “Extra-Heavy” and plots it based on its original gravity (as raw bitumen) of 8.5 degrees rather than referring to its re-engineered gravity (33 degrees).</p>

      <h3>PRELIM Special Cases</h3>
      <h4>Proxy Assays</h4>
      <p>When assays are not available, the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview uses proxy assays, which are deemed to have similar qualities as the crude oil or oil in the gas field. In the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview, the following proxy assays were used:</p>
      <ul>
          <li>Natural and Manmade CO<sub>2</sub> EOR Example cases are run with Equinor’s Angola Girassol assay. </li>
          <li>Nigeria Obagi is modeled using Chevron’s Nigeria Bonny Light assay as a proxy. The crudes ultimately extracted are similar, though the two fields vary widely in their production processes. </li>
          <li>U.S. California Midway Sunset is modeled using Stratiev’s Venezuela Tia Juana assay as a proxy. The Midway Sunset oil field contains very complex oil. The API gravity is highly variable, ranging from the teens to the low twenties. The 1978
              oil assay obtained for OCI Phase 1 indicates a gravity of 22.6, while more recent studies have found a gravity of 12.6 degrees. The Tia Juana assay was chosen as a proxy because it is closer in API gravity, sulfur content, and product yields
              to the current Midway Sunset crude than the original Midway Sunset assay. Note that Midway Sunset crude is priced and tracked monthly as a 13 degree API gravity crude.</li>
          <li>U.S. Texas Eagle Ford oil and gas fields are modeled separately due to the wide range of characteristics (for example, API gravity), as well as production and refining practices, particular to each zone of oil and gas production in the Eagle
              Ford play. The U.S. Eagle Ford Condensate and Volatile Oil PRELIM cases, as well as the U.S. Eagle Ford Gas associated liquids, were run using Equinor’s Eagle Ford Chem Grade assay. The U.S. Eagle Ford Black Oil PRELIM case was run using
              Platts’s Eagle Ford Ultralight assay.</li>
          <li>A proxy crude was selected to model the oil associated with each gas field. For example, a condensate assay was selected to model the oil associated with Argentina Vaca Muerta’s gas production. Details on the proxy assay, if it applies, are
              listed in the Oil Details page for each oil or gas in the OCI<sup>+</sup> Preview.</li>
